Make my Crispy Lemon Hotcakes for your hotcake this Valentine’s Day! 🍋💛 
.
It’s a 1-bowl, 1-pan dessert and comes together in less than 15 minutes so you can focus on…other things❤️‍🔥😏💋
.
📖 Recipe:
Makes 2 small hotcakes
.
~Dry ingredients:
• 1/4 cup all purpose flour
• 1/4 teaspoon baking powder
• 1/4 teaspoon baking soda
• 1/4 teaspoon salt
• 1 teaspoon sugar

~Wet ingredients:
• 1/2 each lemon (juice and zest)
• 1 large egg
• 2 tablespoons full fat Greek yogurt
• 1 teaspoon lemon curd
• 1 tablespoon coconut oil, melted

~For cooking: 
• 2 tablespoons ghee

1. Whisk the dry ingredients in a large bowl. 

2. Add the wet ingredients. Whisk until just combined. Don’t over-mix. Some lumps are fine.

3. Add 1 tablespoon of ghee to a small pan (mine’s about 4 inches) and bring to medium-low heat. Add half of the batter while encouraging it to spread with a spatula. Cook for 2-3 minutes or until the edges are mostly cooked and the batter forms small bubbles on top.

4. Flip gently. Cook for 1-2 minutes or until the hotcake springs back up when you touch it on top.

5. Serve and garnish with preferred toppings. I used lemon curd, vanilla bean ice cream, and lemon zest. 
.

A montadito is a small (typically open faced) sandwich🥖 served as a tapa in Spain🇪🇸. This is my interpretation, made with a crispy skinned 🐟salmon chicharrón💥 (instead of bread).
.
.
💥For chicharrones:
- 8 ounces salmon skins
- 1/2 teaspoon salt 

Preheat your oven to 425 degrees farenheit. Spread the skins straight and flat on a parchment-lined sheet pan. Sprinkle them liberally with salt. Cover them with another sheet of parchment and weigh down with another pan that covers their surface area (to keep them from curling). Bake them for 10-15 minutes or until golden and crispy. Transfer them to a sheet of paper towel to soak the excess oil. Break into bite-size4d pieces. Set them aside at room temperature. 
.
🐟For tartare:
- 8 ounces fresh, wild caught salmon, diced into 1/4 inch cubes
- 1 tablespoon dill, finely chopped
- 1 tablespoon shallots, finely minced
- 1 tablespoon capers, drained, finely chopped
- 1 teaspoon extra virgin olive oil
- 1 each lemon zest
- 1/2-1 teaspoon salt

Combine everything in a medium bowl. Stir and taste. Adjust with more salt if necessary. Serve cold. Spoon desired amount on your chicharrones and serve immediately.
.
🍋For garnish:
- 1 each lemon, wedges
- 2 hard boiled eggs, grated
- 2 tablespoons dill, chopped

Garnish with hardboiled eggs and chopped dill on top. Squeeze lemon on your montaditos when ready to eat. 
.
.
Enjoy! LMK your thoughts in the comments! @tastemade

🌼Spring is here, so I made these elegant, but easy, Lemon Cream Cake Coupes🍋. Make them for Mama tomorrow..💛
.
Recipe below!☀️
.
Makes 6-8 coupes 
.
🌻Ingredients:

8 ounces mascarpone cheese
1 jar (10 ounces) lemon curd
16 ounces heavy whipping cream
1 teaspoon vanilla extract
3 each lemon zest
1/2 teaspoon salt 

1 box (9 ounces) vanilla wafers (ladyfingers would work too)
6-8 ounces orange liqueur (sub. with orange simple syrup for non-alcoholic)
.
In a large bowl, stir 2/3 of the lemon curd into the mascarpone cheese until well combined.

Whisk in 1/3 of the whipping cream until it’s well incorporated and there’s no visible lumps. Then add the rest of the cream, vanilla, zest of 2 lemons, and salt. Whisk until fluffy, but runny. Using a rubber spatula, gently fold in the rest of the lemon curd to create swirly ribbons. 

Build your coupes by layering wafers soaked with liqueur, then adding lemon cream. Repeat until you’ve reached the top, finishing with lemon cream. Cover with plastic wrap and refrigerate for 4 hours. When ready to serve, garnish with the remaining lemon zest.
.
💛Serving Tip: You don’t HAVE to use coupe glasses. You can build a large “lemon cream icebox cake” using this same layering method in a trifle dish or large pan/mold.
.

Here’s my fool-proof method to get the 💥crispiest skin on a salmon filet🐟. I used the belly portion because I like the extra fattiness, but any cut will do.😊
.
🚨Here’s the most important tips to get it right:

1. Let it sit at room temperature for 15 minutes. This will ensure even cooking throughout. 

2. Pat it dry with a paper towel before seasoning. Moisture will prevent it from browning properly in the pan.

3. Gently rub the seasoning in right before it hits the pan. Allowing it to sit with salt will extract it’s moisture and we want to keep that in. 

4. Smoking hot pan means just that: smoke coming out from the neutral flavored oil. Medium heat should suffice, but increase it if necessary (depending on your stovetop). You just don’t want to burn the skin before the center cooks. 

5. Skin side goes down first. Hold it down gently with a spatula for a few seconds until it stays flat on its own. This prevents the skin from curling, ensuring the surface will be crispy throughout, not just the edges. Turn down the heat to medium-low at this point and leave it alone until  the edges of your fish are starting to look opaque (3-8 minutes).

6. Kiss it on the other side now. This means flip it over and allow it to cook until it’s just cooked on the inside (30 seconds - 1 minute). Timing will depend on the thickness of your filet. Leaving it longer may result in overcooking and dry meat. We don’t want that, we want it juicy and glistening. 

7. Serve it with the skin side UP to keep it crispy. Any sauce should go underneath. Again, to keep it crispy. 

Hope these tips help but comment⬇️ if you have additional ❓’s
.

Their gelato is spun in small batches in the same vats they’re served from, which keeps it airy and creamy. So much that I told my friend I wanted seconds. He gave me a slightly judgemental look, so I controlled myself…that day.😅

When I come home after trips I crave fruit and veggies😅. My coconut-chia-oat pudding (recipe below) is the perfect vessel to highlight seasonal fruit. This is my go-to recipe for a slightly sweet and very satisfying breakfast, snack, lunch, dinner, or dessert☺️. And it’s so easy to make! I like to prep a big batch and top it with whatever I have on hand throughout the week. Today I topped mine with mango, cantaloupe, banana, a little honey, and granola for crunch.💥
.
📖Recipe:

Coconut Chia-Oat Pudding🥥
(Makes 4-6 large servings)

1 cup old fashioned rolled oats
5 tablespoons chia seeds 
1 can full fat coconut milk
6 ounces water
1 teaspoon vanilla extract
1 pinch salt 
3 packets stevia

1. Place oats and chia seeds in a 2 quart storage container.

2. Combine the rest of the ingredients in a blender and blend until well combined. 

3. Pour this mixture over the oats and chia seeds. Stir well, cover, and refrigerate for 4 hours. It will get thick and creamy. 

4. Stir well before serving and dilute (if necessary) with water or milk of choice. Top with your favorite fruit or toppings. Keep refrigerated for up to 1 week.

Granita di melone con panna..🧡🤍
Cantaloupe granita with whipped cream..🧡🤍
.
🍧A granita is a light and refreshing Sicilian treat I learned about while visiting this summer. Texture-wise, I’d describe it as a cross between a sorbet and a slushy. It’s spoonable, but a little on the melty side, so it’s often served with both a spoon and a straw. Did I mention it’s dairy free?! Some popular flavors range from almond, pistachio (my favorite), cantaloupe, lemon, strawberry, and coffee. 

🥐Locals order their granita with a soft brioche bun on the side for “scarpetta.” I recently learned about this term, meaning to sop up a sauce with bread. 

☁️In addition to the sweet bun, I’d always order my granita with panna (whipped cream). That’s also optional, but it adds an extra layer of decadence and a great textural icy/creamy contrast. If you know me, you know I’m a sucker for ice cream, so I think dairy is imperative in a sweet, frozen treat.

🍽️Granita makes an acceptable breakfast in Sicily, but also a luxurious snack or dessert. I can attest because I had it for every meal period, sometimes more than once a day, and I didn’t seem to offend any Italians. I had to learn the hard way how seriously they take their meal courses and meal times.🫣🫠

🧡I opted for melone today because it’s the flavor I ordered during my anticipated visit to @bambar_taormina , which was kindly recommended by my talented colleague, @homecookingtherapy 😊. 

☀️This colorful, picturesque cafe sits in the center of the busy, pedestrian-packed streets of Taormina. It’s the perfect spot to sit down, people watch, and cool off from the scorching sun.  Though my version of their granita doesn’t beat that experience, flavor-wise I think I nailed it! Even better, it requires less than a handful of ingredients and only a few minutes of prep time. 

📖I’ll share my recipe very soon, hoping you’ll, too, get a little taste of Sicily. I know I will..🇮🇹

Heirloom Tomato Panzanella 🍅🍞
.
Tomatoes are all the craze now, and rightfully so, they’ve been gorgeous. This dish highlights them without altering their freshness.😋

Traditional panzanella uses stale bread tossed with tomatoes and veggies, which softens the bread. Since I’m using fresh bread, which is still soft, I don’t see a need to toss the tomatoes with it and further soften it. I enjoy the contrasting texture of the lightly crispy, warm bread with the plump, juicy tomatoes. If you have stale bread or prefer it on the softer side, by all means, toss it altogether in a large bowl instead of keeping it separate from the tomatoes.🥖

🐟The umami anchovy oil I made provides a salty flavor contrast to the sweet tomatoes. I’ve included my super simple recipe below. And I hope you won’t be put off by the anchovies😅. Cooking them out, as I do in the video, mellows out their fishiness. They dissolve and transform into a funky, complex flavor enhancer. Pouring that hot oil into the shallots, garlic, and capers does the same. All the pungency softens, the flavors marry each other, and everyone gets happy and comfy together. This allows the raw, fresh tomatoes to shine.🍅✨

I hope you try this simple recipe and enjoy the rest of your summer!☀️

-Mia🤍
.
.
Umami anchovy oil
(Serves 1)

1 small shallot, thinly sliced
4 kalamata olives, minced
1 teaspoon capers
1 teaspoon garlic, minced
2 tablespoons extra virgin olive oil
3 anchovies

In a small, heat-proof bowl, combine the shallots, olives, capers, and garlic. 

In a small saucepan, bring the olive oil to medium heat. It should not smoke. Add in the anchovies and cook them, stirring constantly for 1-3 minutes until they’ve dissolved and start smelling nutty (instead of fishy). Pour this hot oil (with the anchovy bits) into the bowl with the rest of the ingredients and stir it all together. Wait for it to come to room temperature (5-10 minutes) before using.

🍓“Berries & Cream”☁️ 
.
...a no fuss, no bake dessert that will satisfy any sweet tooth. You can swap out the fruit & adjust to seasonality. 🍑Peaches come to mind. Hope you try it & please, lmk what you think in the comments!☺️
.
📖Berries & Cream
4-6 servings (using low ball glasses🥃)
.
🍓Macerated Berries
(Can be made a day ahead)

10 oz. frozen raspberries
1/2 C sugar
1/2 C water 
1 pinch salt 
1 # strawberries, quartered
1 tblsp. vanilla bean paste (or extract)

In a med. pot, simmer the raspberries, sugar, water, & salt at med-low heat for 20-30 mins. or until syrupy. Allow this mixture to cool completely. (HACK- skip this step by sub-ing w/12 oz. of store-bought fruit preserves)

Stir in the strawberries & vanilla bean paste. Transfer to an airtight container & into the fridge. Chill for at least 2 hrs. 
.
🌰Hazelnut Praline

1 C hazelnuts
1/2 C sugar 
2 tblsp. butter
1/2 tsp. flaky sea salt 

In a med. pot, over med. heat, stir the hazelnuts & sugar constantly until the sugar has dissolved, caramelized, & looks shiny. Turn off the heat. Add the butter & stir to combine. Transfer the candied nuts to a parchment-lined pan. While still hot, sprinkle them w/salt. Allow them to cool completely, then break them up into large chunks & pulse them in a food processor until it resembles a coarse, rocky sand texture. Store, covered, at room temp. 
.
☁️Mascarpone Chantilly Cream

8 oz. mascarpone
1 C powdered sugar 
1 tblsp. vanilla bean paste
1 pinch salt
16 oz. heavy cream

In a lg. bowl (or bowl of a stand mixer), add mascarpone, powdered sugar, vanilla bean paste, salt, & half of the heavy cream. Using a mixer w/the whisk attachment, at low speed, whisk all ingredients until they’re just combined & the mixture is smooth. Turn to med. speed. In a slow, steady stream, pour in the rest of your heavy cream. Continue whisking to achieve med. peaks that stand on their own. Transfer to a piping/ziplock bag. Keep cold. 
.

My Gooey S’Mores Tart is the perfect alternative to s’mores if you’re not into sleeping outdoors & building fires (🙋🏼‍♀️it me!). IMO, it’s BETTER. Hope you try it!😊
.
🥥Coconutty graham cracker crust: 

1 ½ C graham cracker crumbs (7.5 oz. box)
1 ½ C unsweetened coconut flakes
⅓ C sugar
½ tsp. salt
1 ½ stick butter (6 oz.), lg. cubes 

1. Preheat your oven to 350F.
2. In a lg. bowl, combine the graham cracker crumbs, coconut, sugar, & salt. 
3. Bring a sm. sauce pot to med-low heat. Add butter & swirl the pot continuously until it foams, smells nutty, & turns golden brown. Scrape all of it into the bowl w/the other ingredients. Mix until it resembles wet sand.
4. Line a 10” springform pan w/parchment. Using a straight edged container, press the mixture evenly about 2” up the sides & throughout the base (should be about ¼ “ thick). 
5. Bake on the center rack for 13-20 mins. or until it turns golden brown. Cool completely at room temp.
.
🥧Gooey S’Mores Tart:
(Serves 6-8)

2 C heavy cream
12 oz. semi sweet choc. chips (I used 46% cacao)
4 tblsp. unsalted butter (2 oz.), lg. cubes 
½ tsp. salt 
1 10” coconutty graham cracker crust
2 C marshmallow creme/fluff (7 oz.)

1. In a med. pot, bring heavy cream to med-low heat or until it steams. 
2. Add choc. chips into a lg. bowl. Pour the hot cream over them. Let sit for 3 mins., then whisk until combined. 
3. Add butter & salt. Whisk again until butter is fully melted & incorporated. 
4. Pour into the cooled tart shell. Refrigerate (uncovered) for 3-4 hrs. or until the ganache is completely firm in the center.
5. W/the back of a spoon, spread the marshmallow creme over it. Using a blowtorch, toast  to your desired color. If you don’t have a blowtorch, broil it on high on the top rack of your oven w/the door open, watching it until it reaches the color you want. Refrigerate for another hr. before slicing. 
.
👩🏼‍🍳Pro Tip: For clean, neat slices, run your knife under hot water, and wipe it dry before each slice.

☀️Summer isn’t over yet and my 🍑Peaches’N Cream☁️ recipe is the perfect 🌞summer-to-fall🍂 transition. A little cinnamon🤎 gives them a little warmth, while the lemon🍋 cookies and zest provide some brightness. Make individual glasses for easy serving, or assemble it in a large, glass trifle dish for a show stopping dessert centerpiece.✨
.
📖 Peaches’n Cream Recipe
(Serves 8-10)
.
🍑Spiced peaches:

2 tablespoons butter
5 large peaches, peeled & cubed into 1” chunks
1/2 teaspoon cinnamon
1/4 cup cane sugar
1 pinch salt

In a medium pot over medium heat, brown the butter until it smells nutty. 
Add the rest of the ingredients and saute for 5-10 minutes until a caramel starts to form. 
Add 1/4 cup of water, reduce heat to low, and simmer for 2-5 minutes or until the water evaporates and the peaches look saucy and glossy. 
Transfer the peaches to a heat-proof container and chill in the fridge for 1-2 hours or until they’re cold to the touch. 
.
☁️Mascarpone Cream:

7 ounces mascarpone cheese (1 pkg.)
1 teaspoon vanilla
3/4 cup powdered sugar
1 pinch salt
16 ounces heavy whipping cream 

Add mascarpone, vanilla, sugar, salt, and 3 tablespoons of the whipping cream into a large bowl. 
Whisk everything together until the mixture is smooth and has no visible lumps of sugar. 
Add the rest of the cream slowly while whisking until it’s fully incorporated then whisk until stiff peaks form. 
Transfer to a piping bag (or a ziplock bag) and refrigerate. 
.
✨Assembly:

1 batch mascarpone cream, chilled
1 batch spiced peaches, chilled
4 cups crushed cookies (14 ounces approx. - lemon, shortbread, sugar, or any cookie that will compliment the peaches and cinnamon)
2 lemons, zest

Assemble by layering in individual glasses or in a large, glass bowl or trifle dish and serve by-the-scoop. 
Can be assembled up to 2 days ahead of time for a softer, cakey texture on the cookies.
.
.

🌽My sweet corn cream soup is perfect for this indecisive ☀️summmer-fall🍂 transitional weather. It’s equally comforting when served hot on a 🥶chilly day or cold on a 🥵hot day.

📖Full recipe 👇🏼:
.
🥒Cucumber Salsa
(Serves 3-4)

1 C quartered cherry tomatoes
1 C small diced cucumbers
1/2 C finely minced red onion
1 tbsp. chopped cilantro
1 tbsp. chopped dill
1 ea. lime, zest & juice
1/2 tsp. salt
1 tbsp. extra virgin olive oil
1 tsp. chipotle paste or hot sauce (optional)

Combine all the ingredients in a lg. bowl. Allow it to sit at room temp. for 30 mins. Taste it. The flavor of the grassy-lemony herbs & sweet tomatoes should come through. Adjust the flavor w/more salt if necessary. 
Stir well before serving. 
Store in the fridge for up to 3 days. 
.
🌽Sweet corn cream soup
(Serves 3-4) 

2 tbsp. olive oil
1 med. onion, thinly sliced
3 lg. stalks celery, thinly sliced
16 oz. (yellow corn kernels(fresh or frozen)
1/2 tsp. salt
1 tsp. garlic, minced 
1 qt. Broth (chicken or vegetable)
1/2 C cashews, raw
1/2 tsp. turmeric, ground
1 C crushed tortilla chips

In a med. pot at med. heat, add olive oil, onion, celery, 3/4’s of your corn, & salt. Sauté, stirring occasionally for 5-10 mins. or until the veggies are soft & the onion/celery are translucent. 
Add the garlic. Sauté until it’s aromatic (about 45 secs).
Add the broth. Bring to a simmer for 5 mins.
Transfer everything to a high speed blender. Work in batches if necessary. Add the cashews & turmeric. Blend at the highest speed for 2-3 minutes or until velvety smooth & creamy. 
Pour it all back into the pot with the rest of the corn. Bring it back to a simmer. 
Taste. The flavor of the corn should come through w/a hint of sweetness. 
Add more salt if necessary. 
Serve hot or bring it to room temp. & chill it in the fridge to serve cold. Garnish it w/my fresh cucumber salsa (above) & crushed crunchy corn tortillas or croutons.
Store the soup in the fridge for up to 3 days. 
.
.

🧓🏻Abuela’s Pollo en Fricasé🇵🇷
.
To keep things EXTRA, I added Crispy Chicharrones!💥💁🏼‍♀️ And if you rrrreally wanna eat like a local🇵🇷, don’t forget a slice of aguacate!!🥑
.
🍗🥘Chicken Fricasé with Chicharrones💥

📖Makes 3-4 servings

Ingredients:

6 bone-in chicken thighs &/or drumsticks, skins removed & reserved
1 ½  tbsp adobo
2 tsp salt
4 tbsp olive oil 
½ C sofrito (recipe in reels)
2 C tomatoes, sm dice
7 green olives w/pimentos, minced
1 tbsp sazón
6 cups chicken broth
2 cups carrots, peeled, lg dice
3 yukon gold potatoes, peeled, lg dice
¼ C cilantro, chopped

-Preheat oven to 400F.
-Rub adobo and 1 tsp of salt all over chicken & skins. (🚨Omit the salt here if your adobo has it!)
-Stretch out skins on a parchment-lined sheet pan. Bake @ 400F for 15-20 mins or until golden & crispy. Place on a paper towel to soak excess fat & set aside @ room temp.
-In a lg pot, at med heat, add olive oil & sear chicken for 2-3 mins on all sides or until deep golden brown. Remove from pot & set aside.
-Add sofrito. Cook, stirring for 2-3 mins, until moisture has evaporated. 
-Add olives, tomatoes, & cook, stirring for 5-7 minutes until tomatoes are soft & saucy.
-Add sazón, remaining salt, and stir. (🚨Omit the salt here if your sazón has it!) Add chicken back in then the broth and carrots. Cover and simmer at med-low heat for 25 minutes. 
-Add potatoes. Simmer, uncovered, for 15-20 more minutes or until potatoes are fork tender. Mash 1-2 up & add back into the sauce to thicken for 1-2 more mins. 
-Taste, adjust seasoning w/more salt if necessary, & add cilantro.
-Serve over rice with sliced avocado & crushed chicken chicharrones.
.

🇵🇷Mayo-Ketchup is a universal sauce used in many different applications in Puerto Rican cuisine. The base consists of just that: mayonnaise and ketchup. Add-ins vary from home to home, including hot sauce, garlic, mustard, vinegar, spices, and herbs. You can even find pre-made versions in grocery stores in the ketchup/dressing section. 🛒

Mayo-Ketchup was my dip of choice growing up in Puerto Rico (🙅🏼‍♀️no ketchup for me, thx). 🧓🏻Abuela always made it for me and served it along her tostones and sorullitos (cornmeal fritters). I’d also smear it into my burgers, hot dogs, and fries…or drizzled into a tripleta (triple meat sando). 🍟🍔🌭

Cashew-Ketchup is my healthy-ish, guiltless version that I PROMISE will deliver in flavor and ease of preparation! LMK what you think! 😊
:
📖Recipe:

🤍Cashew “Mayo”
(Makes 1 cup)

1/2 cup raw cashews 
1/2 cup water 
2 each garlic cloves
1 teaspoon salt
2 teaspoons apple cider vinegar

Blend all ingredients at full speed in a high-speed blender for 1-2 minutes or until the sides of the blender are warm and the mixture looks creamy. Store in a jar, refrigerated, for up to 3 days. 

🚨**If you don’t have a high-speed blender, soak your cashews in water overnight and drain before using.
:
🩷Cashew Ketchup
(Makes 1 1/2 cup)

1 cup cashew “mayo”
1/3 cup ketchup
2 teaspoons sriracha (optional)

Whisk or blend all your ingredients together until homogenous. Store in a jar, refrigerated, for up to 3 days. 
.

Sorullitos🌽🇵🇷
:
🧓🏻Abuela makes these in the morning to serve with our cafecito☕️ or as an afternoon snack, with Mayo-Ketchup on the side, for dipping☀️. These are sweet/savory cornmeal fritters. They’re soft and creamy on the inside and crispy all around. Abuela forms them by hand, one by one, with tapered tips. This is my easy, make-ahead, no-frying, lazy girl version💁🏼‍♀️. Hope you try them!🤍
:
📖Recipe:
(Makes 42)

💦3 cups water
🌽1 1/2 cup enriched fine yellow cornmeal 
🧂1 1/2 teaspoon salt
🧈1 tablespoon butter

Spray a square, 9 inch pan, with olive oil or ghee. Line it with parchment so it hangs about 4 inches off each side. Spray the parchment and the exposed sides of the pan again.

Add all ingredients into a medium pot, then turn to medium heat. Start stirring with a spatula immediately. Continue stirring constantly for 5-10 minutes until the mixture starts to thicken and forms a smooth, clean dough that separates from the sides of the pot. 

Transfer the dough to your prepared pan and, while it’s still warm, flatten it with your spatula into an even layer that takes up the entire surface. Spray the top with olive oil or ghee and cover it with the parchment that hangs off. Refrigerate it for 30 minutes to 1 hour or until it’s completely firm (or overnight if making ahead).

Preheat the oven to 475 degrees Fahrenheit. Then, line a flat sheet pan with parchment paper and spray it liberally with olive oil or ghee. 

Using the parchment on top of your dough as handles, remove the dough from the pan. Slice into 1/2 inch X 3 inch rectangles to form sorullitos. Transfer them to your prepared sheet pan, spaced at least 1/2 inch apart. Spray them again on top with olive oil or ghee. Bake them for 20 minutes, flipping them over halfway through, or until they’re golden on all sides and crispy. (You can also make these in the air fryer).

Serve them with Mayo-Ketchup on the side for dipping. You can find my recipe on my previous Reel.

I flavored mine with cinnamon, vanilla, and a little whiskey to bring out that vanilla flavor, which I love. But this recipe is easily customizable. You can swap out the spices, add nut pastes, @nutella , and substitute the whiskey for other liqueurs like almond @disaronno_official , hazelnut @frangelico , coffee @kahlua or orange @grandmarnierofficial . Which one’s your favorite?☺️
:
Classic Coquito 🥥🇵🇷
(Makes 2 liters)

1 can coconut milk
1 can evaporated milk
1 can cream of coconut (Coco López is a famous brand)
1 can sweetened condensed milk
1-2 cups Puerto Rican rum (I used 2 cups @donqrum )

My add-ons:

1 teaspoon cinnamon
2 teaspoons vanilla bean paste
2 teaspoons vanilla extract
3/4 cups @woodfordreserve whiskey
1/2 teaspoon salt 

1. Blend all the ingredients for 1 minute. 
2. Bottle it into recycled bottles while it’s freshly blended (to promote even distribution of spices). 
3. Chill it overnight and shake well before serving (chilled). 

Store in the fridge for up to one month.
